The paper deals with algorithms for solving the Palindrome Problem and the Longest Palindromic Substring Problem in the streaming model, which involves processing data as it arrives over time and using sublinear space. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves randomized algorithms, which are often studied in the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. The paper also deals with combinatorial problems, such as finding palindromes, which are often studied in the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The paper also involves information theory, as it deals with the amount of space required to solve the problems, which suggests that it may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves machine learning, as it discusses practical problems related to palindromes, which suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
